      "cols": [
        "Finding/Observation",
        "Description (Example)",
        "General Interpretation / Significance (Example)"
      ],
      "rows": [
        [
          "Single tract, low course",
          "One straight channel below sphincter",
          "Simple fistula, easier surgery"
        ],
        [
          "Multiple branches, high extension",
          "Tracts crossing levator ani or up to rectum",
          "Complex fistula, staged surgery likely"
        ],
        [
          "Fluid collection >2 cm",
          "Rim-enhancing pus pocket",
          "Active abscess, needs drainage"
        ],
        [
          "Enhancement at internal opening",
          "Bright spot at dentate line",
          "Confirmed internal opening for seton placement"
        ],
        [
          "Inflammation / Contrast Enhancement",
          "Following gadolinium administration, there is avid enhancement of the fistula tract walls and the walls of the associated abscess. Surrounding soft tissues show moderate inflammatory stranding.",
          "Indicates active fistulous inflammation or infection, guiding timing of treatment and monitoring, particularly relevant in Crohn’s disease."
        ],
        [
          "Secondary Tracts / Ramifications",
          "A secondary ‘horseshoe’ tract is noted extending from the primary tract posteriorly and coursing towards the left ischioanal fossa, without a distinct external opening on the left side.",
          "Denotes complex fistula. All branches must be identified and addressed to prevent recurrence. Horseshoe tracts may require bilateral drainage."
        ],
        [
          "Other Pelvic Findings",
          "The visualized portions of the levator ani muscles appear normal. No other significant pelvic pathology is identified within the field of view.",
          "Exclusion of other pelvic abnormalities (e.g., tumors, proctitis, fistulas from Crohn’s) is important for complete patient evaluation."
        ]
      ]
    },
    "faqs": [
      {
        "question": "Is the scan painful?",
        "answer": "No. You’ll feel only the table movement and hear knocking sounds.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "How soon can I resume normal activities?",
        "answer": "Immediately after the scan unless sedation is used.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "Will I need a follow-up scan?",
        "answer": "Yes, often 3–6 months post-surgery to confirm healing.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "What if I’m allergic to contrast?",
        "answer": "Serious reactions are extremely rare. Tell the technologist about previous allergies; pre-medication is available.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "Can MRI detect cancer in fistula tracts?",
        "answer": "Yes, unusual thickening or enhancement prompts further evaluation.\n"
      },
      {
        "question": "What is the approximate MRI fistulogram cost at Cadabams Diagnostics?",
        "answer": "The **MRI Fistulogram cost** can vary depending on several factors, including the complexity of the scan, whether contrast dye is used, and your specific insurance coverage. For precise pricing information for an **MRI Fistulogram** at Cadabams Diagnostics, please contact our billing department directly or visit our website. We can provide details on current rates and help you understand your insurance benefits."
      }
    ],
